{
  "comment_text": {
    "snp1.3:15.2": "The exact nuance of this line is hard to pin down. Later Pali texts equate <i lang='pi' translate='no'>abhilāpa</i> with “naming”, but it doesn’t seem to occur in any early texts with this sense. However <i lang='pi' translate='no'>lapanā</i> is used in the sense of “flattery” in eg. <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn117/en/sujato#29.2'>MN 117:29.2</a>. ",
    "snp1.3:19.2": "<i lang='pi' translate='no'>Padumī</i> is a word for “elephant”, after the lotus-like spots or mottles on an elephant’s body, or else due to their fondness for lotuses (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>padmaprasaktyā</i>, Mātaṅgalīla); elephants are often seen bathing and eating in lotus ponds. ",
    "snp1.3:22.2": "The reference is to the smelting of gold, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/an3.101/en/sujato#1.9'>AN 3.101:1.9</a>. "
  },
